</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MEMPHIS AFTERNOONS by James Conaway (Avon: $10; 211 pp.). The author of "Napa" 
traces the threads of the disparate families united by his parent's marriage in 
this fond memoir.Although both clans include numerous eccentrics in the great 
Southern tradition, Conaway's most distinguished ancestor was J. P. Alley, an 
editorial cartoonist honored for his criticism of the Ku Klux Klan during the 
early 1920s. Conaway uses his skills as a novelist to evoke a nostalgic vision 
of the South, where ice cubes tinkle in pitchers on shaded porches, although 
the reader is left with the feeling that the author is both recalling his past 
and attempting to exorcise it. 
</P>
