<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ACROSS THE TOP OF THE WORLD: To the North Pole by Sled, Balloon, Airplane and 
Nuclear Ice Breaker by David E. Fisher (Delta: $11.95; 305 pp., illustrated). 
In 1991, Fisher sailed to the North Pole on the Sovetskiy Soyuz, a nuclear ice 
breaker designed to serve as a luxury liner although most of its promised 
amenities proved illusory.His account of the hard-drinking, often comic boreal 
voyage provides an agreeable sugar coating for an overview of the attempts to 
reach that dubious landmark. Most of the narrative focuses on the conflicting 
claims of Frederick Cook and Robert Peary, neither of whom actually reached the 
North Pole -- despite the honors Peary received. The Pole itself proves 
anticlimactic: It's just a bitterly cold chunk of floating ice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
