<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS PICKS: 'HOFFA' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This atypical 1992 film biography of the Teamsters' Jimmy Hoffa is a very 
impressive piece of work in a number of ways. Dark, sinister and brooding, it 
uses the convincing acting of Jack Nicholson (pictured) in the title role, 
Stephen H. Burum's panoramic cinematography and Danny DeVito's polished, 
energetic direction (he also stars as a Hoffa ally) to create a stark, brassy 
epic of union history. But " Hoffa" turns out to be as misdirected as it is 
passionate, a take-it-or-leave-it biography that disdains all the conventions 
of the form (Cinemax Monday at 10 p.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</TEXT>
