</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLITICAL PERENNIAL STASSEN IS RUNNING AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Harold Stassen, 87, the 10-time presidential candidate whose name has become 
synonymous with unsuccessful campaigns, has joined the Republican race for the 
U.S. Senate. Stassen, a former Minnesota governor, announced Friday that he is 
seeking his party's nomination for the seat held by retiring Republican Sen. 
Dave Durenberger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071794-0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 061567 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 17, 1994, Sunday, Bulldog Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 1; Column 1; Advance Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1466 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MCDONALD'S MASSACRE; TIME CAN'T HEAL ALL WOUNDS INFLICTED BY 21 SLAYINGS; 
