<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA 1994; TICKETS AVAILABLE, BUT . . . ; SOCCER: SEATS ALL OVER THE 
ROSE BOWL CAN BE BOUGHT FOR TODAY'S FINAL, BUT PRICES ARE GOING UP. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT WHITE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A survey of local ticket brokers on Saturday during the World Cup consolation 
game found tickets for today's final available at inflated rates and going 
quickly. 
</P>
<P>
 The highest demand -- and biggest price hikes -- were for the Cup's least 
expensive tickets, Category III. 
</P>
<P>
 When contacted at about 1 p.m., a broker at Ticket Outlet's Pasadena store 
said its Category III tickets had sold out an hour earlier, selling for at 
least $300. 
</P>
<P>
 Musical Chairs tickets in Brentwood had sold out of Category III tickets 
"about five minutes ago," when contacted next, though Category II seats were 
available for $550 and two remaining Category I seats were $750. 
</P>
<P>
 The Beverly Hills' Ticket Outlet location had the priciest listings, with top 
Category I tickets at $1,250. The cheapest Category I was $750. 
</P>
<P>
 The three categories of tickets for the final sold with face values of $475 
for Category I, the best seats, mostly between the goal lines; $300 for 
Category II in the Rose Bowl's corners; and $180 for Category III, primarily 
behind the goal. 
</P>
<P>
 Applause Tickets in Encino had Category I beginning at $500, but was sold out 
of Category IIIs listed at $325. 
</P>
<P>
 And Good Time Tickets in Hollywood was asking $350 for Category III tickets -- 
almost double the face value -- but had Category I tickets beginning at face 
value. 
</P>
<P>
 Prices were similar at VIP tickets in Sherman Oaks, with Category I tickets 
selling for as little as $500, with IIIs beginning at $375. 
</P>
<P>
 Al Brooks ticket agency was sold out of Category I and II, but wanted $425 -- 
2 1/2 times face value -- for behind-the-goal Category III seats. 
</P>
<P>
 Ticket Time in Los Angeles was asking a little less than most for III -- $325 
-- but had Category I in several places, with varying prices. 
</P>
<P>
 A near-list $525 could get tickets in the 60th row, but up-close seats between 
the penalty areas were $950. 
</P>
<P>
 The Beverly Hills Ticket Outlet, they of the $1,250 seat, wanted $450 for 
Category III. 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County brokers were more likely to be sold out than L.A. brokers, 
possibly because of the heavy influx of ticket-hungry Brazilian fans into the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
 Night On The Town in Santa Ana was sold out, Ticket Outlet's Anaheim office 
had only Category III for $450 each or $800 for a pair, and Megan's Tickets in 
Irvine had only Category I seats remaining for $750. 
</P>
</TEXT>
