<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NEXT LOS ANGELES / TURNING IDEAS INTO ACTION; HUMAN RELATIONS; WILL LOS 
ANGELES CREATE A MODEL OF VITALITY BY SHAPING COMMON GOALS, OR WILL IT 
DISINTEGRATE INTO A MODERN-DAY BABEL?; SOLUTIONS; TEACH KIDS TO THINK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FROM: Cheryl Greer, 39, a faculty member of Pacific Oaks College in Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
 Greer, who leads seminars and workshops on diversity training, proposes that 
school districts introduce an anti-bias perspective in their curricula -- 
beginning in preschool -- that teaches children to be critical thinkers. 
</P>
<P>
 Such a curriculum recognizes and explores differences in people by including 
diversity in all subject matter. It is not a separate discipline, like ethnic 
studies. Such a perspective shows diversity as the norm and allows children to 
decide what is fair and unfair. It talks about ways to effect change. REALITY 
CHECK 
</P>
<P>
 This can happen, at least on a limited scale. Implementing anti-bias curricula 
on a large scale might be difficult given the politics of local school boards 
and the intense competition and review process for public school textbooks. The 
notion might catch on more quickly in private schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
