<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NEXT LOS ANGELES / TURNING IDEAS INTO ACTION; HOW CAN WE TAKE ADVANTAGE OF 
THE MOSAIC OF ENTREPRENEURSHIP THAT MAKES BUSINESS LIFE SO VITAL IN SOUTHERN 
CALIFORNIA?; SOLUTIONS; GIVE MOVIES A STARRING ROLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FROM: Jeff Berg, chairman of International Creative Management, one of the 
nation's largest talent agencies. 
</P>
<P>
 Many familiar Southern California businesses -- movies, television, 
telecommunications, publishing -- will be redefining their operations in the 
next few years.And those businesses employ directly and indirectly 534,000 
people and contribute $16.3 billion to the Southern California economy. 
</P>
<P>
 So, Berg says, it is important that Los Angeles remain a major part of the 
global information industry. 
</P>
<P>
 The area needs to do more than expedite permits for movie production. "We want 
a new partnership with our institutions of higher learning: Caltech, UCLA, USC, 
CalArts, the Cal State schools, the Claremont Colleges," says Berg. REALITY 
CHECK: 
</P>
<P>
 Universities are already focusing on information sciences, but they are also 
chronically short of money. The entertainment industry could endow more 
academic chairs and companies could gain big public relations points by 
donating time and money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
